Now the White House of Trump has targeted the Statue of Freedom.
The most reliable sign of regime change is when it starts to fight the statues.
The Americans understand this as well as everyone else -- hence the deliberate theatrical demolishing of the statue of Saddam Hussain at the Firdo Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of Trump's key ideologists, no doubt knew what he was doing when he brought the symbolic axe over the Statue of Freedom during a violent dispute with CNN journalist Jim Acosta about the President's proposals to sharply reduce legal migration.
Let's be honest, Miller didn't attempt the statue itself.
The regiments of pleasure boats and artists representing the Statue of Freedom would lynch it if he tried to do so.
But he tried to make sense of it, and especially of what was attributed to it in 1903, 17 years after the monument was completed, when the poems of Emma Lazarus were added to the pedestal.
As Miller groaned at Acosta, "I don't want to go deep into history here, but the Statue of Freedom is... a symbol of American freedom that enlightens the world.
The poem you're talking about was later added and is not part of the original Statue of Freedom."
Miller put the facts right, but as he himself said, it's not really about history.
It's about the current resounding words of Lazarus, the only ones in which the state does not invite any immigrants, but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / your crowds dreaming of breathing freely / the miserable waste of your vast shores."
Never before have "unlucky trash" been so visible on our screens.
Miller didn't do literature -- he made it clear that in America Trump didn't expect these people.
This dispute about the meaning of the statue is part of a broader political and cultural war: it is indeed a dispute about the meaning of America.
Lazarus -- and her friends who struggled to put her words in the middle of the statues after her death -- were very well aware that they were doing a completely political act.
It was intended to indicate the link between the French and the American republics by means of a banal classic figure, a woman's image of freedom.
Lazarus changed its meaning: in her poem, a woman's figure is no longer abstract; she has a voice.
And she got a completely different name: Mother of the Exiles.
The combination of poems and images was a brilliant feminist move and a devastating attack against American nativism.
And as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right ones did change it back.
Public Rush Limbo, a sort of John the Baptizer who announced the arrival of Trump in 2010, argued that freedom did not invite anyone, rather she was an early neoconservative carrying the flames of America lying in the darkness of the world: "Freedom goes on.
