Michel Carter's conviction for reporting that led to Conrad Roy's suicide
A resident of Massachusetts was sentenced to two and a half years' imprisonment for having caused the suicide of her boyfriend, Conrad Roy, by means of text messages and telephone calls.
Michael Carter, who is now 20 years old, will have to serve 15 months in prison and five more years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on 13 July 2014.
Roy's father said at the Thursday's hearing, "My family died of grief.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was allowed to remain free until the appeal.
She was threatened with a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy had mental problems.
Carter, wearing red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the sentence standing, holding her hands together and lowering her eyes.
"With her actions she killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor declared to the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve hers.
She did not accept responsibility," she said.
"She didn't show any repentance."
But Carter's lawyer said it was "a tragic case of which she deeply regrets."
However, Judge Lawrence Monice said that in his opinion, her "age, maturity or even mental illness did not affect her behaviour in a noticeable way."
The prosecutor read out a statement from Roy Lynn Roy's mother saying, "It's never been a day that I would not mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I manage -- I'm trying to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever," he says.
Roy's sister, Camdin Roy, said that she was incessantly haunted by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
"Leave the man who has always been with me since I was born is the pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life," she said.
This case is likely to be a legal case, since there is no law in Massachusetts that provides for the responsibility for counseling a person to commit suicide.
In 2014 when Roy was found dead in the car with symptoms of carbon poisoning, he was 17 years old.
The case drew the attention of the entire country when it became known that he had been prompted to commit suicide by a message from Carter.
"You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife, there are many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before he died while he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before she committed suicide, she wrote, "You have to do it, Conrad," and "You just have to turn on the engine, and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monice said that Carter wanted attention by means of Roy's death and prevented her from communicating with the press in order to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
The opinions of the lawyers on this matter were divided.
One of the few people who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 for the murder of her British apartment neighbour in Italy and acquitted two years later.
The 30-year-old Knox published in The Los Angeles Times her separate opinion, which stated, "Michel Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
