In addition to prompt interviews and team profiles, the product provides a company's heat map and illustrates which units have more complaints and which managers have a low rating of approval, which allows it to understand why.
The companies are somewhat aware that they need to control the workplace, otherwise they will become the next Uber who was involved in the scandal when a former employee published a blog describing the aggressive environment in which those who expressed discontent were punished.
For startups like "Glint," this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for a profitable business.
The "Let's Talk About Payment" Internet Portal, dedicated to financial technology, estimates that the global management, management and alignment industry may cost over $118.7 billion by 2020.
The "Converscent" launch from Denver, Colorado, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behaviour, observed a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year, amid the fall in Uber's reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber appeared among the clients.
Like Glint, "Conversent" allows companies to send customized feedback interviews, collect confidential responses in real time and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a helpline for anonymous text messages that allows staff to report bad behaviour.
And if the top manager gets involved, the complaints go directly to the directorate.
"The Court of Public Opinion has seized power from the inspectors," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company treats employees badly or behaves unethically, even if the inspector does not intervene, the company may face expensive consequences of client boycotts, employee outflows and legal proceedings, reported Quinlan.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees in 500 facilities, used Convercent for over a year to make sure that the employees were aware of the rules and procedures and to suggest a simple way to contact the company's head office.
Earlier, if the staff member wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look for a telephone number or a head office email, file a formal complaint and hope that it would be taken seriously.
Often this was a frightening and awkward experience, reported James Vitrano, the head of the law department of Ruby Tuesday, who said that there was no normal way to monitor complaints by employees.
Now that the company uses the Convercent service, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay – can be quickly detected and addressed.
