“And we defend our shareholders from the trials of the staff members.”
According to Queensland, companies began to take employee ethics, values and engagement more seriously in 2002 after Arthur Andersen's accounting firm collapsed because of ethical abuses as a result of the Dela Enron.
But it was only when social networks became widespread that companies realized that they would not be able to keep their dirty underwear from spreading the virus online.
"Before starting to use technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both "Glint" and "Conversent" offer their software as a service, charging companies regularly for the use of their products.
It's a business model and an opportunity that has received approval from venture capitalists who have supported both startups.
In February, "Conversent" received funding of $10 million from companies such as "Sapphire Ventures" and "Tola Capital", bringing the company's total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Besser Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The growing volume of research shows that today's employees expect more from their jobs than they did before.
In markets with strong competition, such as the Silicon Valley, high wages, and interesting projects, these are just the necessary minimum.
The employees want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated and that they are dedicating their time to companies with a positive mission.
"When people are happy to work in a company, feel that they are being heard, and that the work they do is producing results, they're trying harder to make such a company a success," says Nina McQueen, Vice President for Global Entitlements and Satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Conversent and Glint are used.
Investment earns income when companies from their wallets are doing well; companies are doing well when employees are committed and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase the dedication and engagement of staff members, it is not surprising that they find support.
According to cultural professionals in the workplace, it is important to have data on employee engagement.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks for feedback from its employees, it can create the impression that change is coming.
And if change doesn't come fast enough, or if it doesn't come at all, it can become a disappointment, and the employees lose interest.
"If you're going to ask for 4,000 offers, you have to be ready to hold 4,000 interviews," said Russell Rut, president of the management firm of Kotter International, who had to see companies making a mistake relying too much on data collection.
"Because if you don't go to the end, the employees will wonder, "Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why shouldn't I care?"
According to Errett, a company called Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly interviews with employees, is able to take action on the same day that someone reports the problem with Glint.
