Red meat and chocolate are commonly considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help to reduce symptoms of inflaming intestinal diseases.
It's an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, leading to tumbling and excrement, chronic or bloody diarrhea, loss of weight, and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to reduce symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at the University of Washington found that the main amino acid triptophon protein is contributing to the production of immunocells that increase the intestinal acceptability of the intestine.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that the intestine cells in the intestine are making sure that dangerous microbes coming with food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of triggering an inflammatory process are balanced with cells that increase tolerance by protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too severe in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory intestinal diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice with a certain microbial in their intestines have increased cell tolerance.
And this is a microbial that needs triptophon -- one of the building elements of the protein -- to trigger the emergence of these cells.
Professor Colonna said, "We have established a link between one species of microbial, Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of the normal intestinal microbiomy, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more triptophon was contained in the mice's diet, the more these immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same thing would work for people: a combination of L. reuteri and a rich triptophon diet can contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflaming environment in the intestines.
The postmortem of Dr. Louis Cervantes-Barraganwas, in a study of a variety of increasing immune cells, found that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group, which belonged to the same line but was kept separately, did not have them.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by mice microbioms -- communities of germs, viruses and mushrooms that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the intestine cells has been sequented and six species of microbials present in mice with immune cells but not in mice without them have been detected.
Mouses grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiomy and did not develop this kind of immune cell received L. reuteri, and they had immunocells.
In order to understand how microbials affect the immune system, researchers raised L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then moved small portions of the fluid -- without the microbials -- to uninfected immune cells separated from mice.
Immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of triptophon processing, known as idol-3 milk acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of triptophon in mice's food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the triptophon level was halved, the number of cells also doubled.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same more tolerate cell as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastric tract.
It is not known whether by-products of the L. reuteri have contributed to the development of cells in humans, as in mice, but people with inflammable intestinal diseases have found faults in triptophon-related genes.
She says, "Perhaps we need to increase the development of these cells, because these cells affect the inflammatory processes on the inside of the intestines.
