The bill for the White House cost tax payers thousands of dollars.
According to military records provided by the magazine TIME, the White House's decision last month to bring a Marine Helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost the tax payers $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One" when the president is on board, became a central part of the 17 July White House event at which American construction programs were shown.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials examined the technology products from all 50 states.
A helicopter made in Connecticut was placed next to a boat from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a trucker from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the division responsible for managing the Helicopter, the White House Military Authority ordered the presence of the Helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO", only 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an "unusual" event.
"I just wanted you to make sure you knew because this is an unusually well-publicized event," wrote HMX-1 in an e-mail to its supervisor, the first deputy airmaster of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on 17 July to attend an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and remain there until the lawn is released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to return in accordance with the working hours.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the course of the event, while the guard of the unit remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear whether a second crew was required as a result of the log "TIME".
The Hatch Act forbids federal employees from using State property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 specified whether the activity was in conflict with that order.
"We asked, among other things, whether it was a breach of Hatch's law, and we were told no," wrote the commanding officer.
"It seems you have nowhere to go," the deputy chief replied.
The "Done in America" event was declared by the White House as an official event and was not subject to Hatch's law.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance the reform of the health care that was then being prepared by the Senate and lauded attempts to govern government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as "Marine One" and "air Force One" for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it's unusual to ask for them only in the interest of photographic capabilities.
Trump was already the subject of discussions in February when the President's plane flew in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was full of complaints about the use of the Presidential plane by his predecessor.
"The White House is excited about the "made in America" show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials," said Lyndsey Walters, the deputy secretary of the White House.
HMX-1 crews often carry out training flights around the Washington Agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the President of the United States to transport to the White House to exactly an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 in Germany in early July, HMX-1 carried out fifty-eight training landings at the White House.
One of the officials said that the flight carried out for the "Done in America" event was counted as part of the necessary training flights in a month.
The unit's rotary-wing aircraft also flew for 11 additional hours on that day as part of the “non-Presidential support tasks”.
According to the White House, tax payers were not paid for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of Sikorsky reported that the company had not participated in the organization of a demonstration of a helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not account for the budget for Presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the time-rate of the Department of Defence for the fiscal year 2017, the VH-3D rate is US$24,380 per flight hour.
The unit's records indicate that the flight time in the air was 30 minutes each direction from its airstrip at the Quantico Marine Airbase in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than that rate.
“The calculation of the value for the tax payers based on an estimated rate of compensation is quite wrong,” says Walters.
“These approximate rates include staff, services and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual allocation.
According to a study carried out by the RAND corporation in 2015, the rates of compensation do not include the cost of the troops, but do take into account the costs of fuel, maintenance and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, the former White House spokesperson, Sean Spicer, spoke out to defend the use of the helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to show this week what's done in America," said Spicer.
"And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we're all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have been working so hard on.
Therefore, of course, it is perfectly appropriate to pay attention to this."
It was not clear whether Trump was interacting with a helicopter by examining the South Lawn during the event, but he was exactly sitting in the driver's car.
