The National Union of Unskilled, Municipal and Boiled Workers (GMB) is concerned about the investment in the McVitee's factory in Glasgow
The trade union requires guarantees from the managers of the biscuit manufacturer McVitee's in connection with its long-term obligation to produce at the Glasgow factory.
The Scottish branch of GMB reports that the company has ignored the issue of future investments on the Ukrainian site.
A factory that produces, among other products, Hobnobs and Rich Tea cookies employs more than 500 people.
Pladis, the owner of the McVitie's, reports that over five million pounds have been invested in the facility in the last few years.
The company adds that, in the event of any change in the operation of the site, employees and trade union representatives “are the first to know about them”.
In a letter to the head of the company's facility, the Scottish GMB branch demanded that McVitee's react to the concern that funding would not be used to upgrade production lines.
Drew Duffy, a senior organizer, said: "The members of our union are deeply concerned that we cannot get clarity from the general manager of the business needs and investment plan for the future of Tolcross."
The families have worked here for generations, and the concentration of workers is great in local society and in the Greater Glasgow; this is the most important pillar of decent work in the area of high unemployment and social deprivation.
Thus, in terms of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the background of Brexit, the growth of the living minimum and the chronic decline in production, the East End Glasgow desperately needs prosperity in the McVitie's factory.
According to the representative of Pladis, "The head of the Ukrainian facility only yesterday received a letter from the Scottish branch of the GMB, and the company will respond immediately, as we appreciate our continued cooperation with the employees and trade union representatives."
Two months ago, we held a regular meeting in Tolcross with GMB staff and representatives, at which we openly discussed a number of issues.
We talked to the staff that, like all companies working in the most competitive and unstable economic environment, we are constantly re-evaluating our actions – and that applies to all our facilities and activities – in order to remain competitive.
"In recent years, we have invested more than 5 million pounds in our Ukrainian facility, especially in production lines and improvements in performance."
We are fully aware of the value of Tolcross as a production facility, and if there is any change in the work at this site, workers and trade union representatives will be the first to know it."
